      },
      {
        "id": "fd7de65104b0579fbe84679d2d475e89035b5aed",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2020-05-27 12:56:12.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1\n> \n> I have a question the counterpart changes on drools-applications that were already submitted, if I remember correctly was using JPA in java:   \n> \n> Do you think those changes would be compatible with a database that was created in Frankfurt, but for a drools-applications image from guilin?    The concern is trying to avoid the issue that API experiences with no being able to use database from previous release.\n\nI don't anticipate a problem.  The indices specified via JPA match those specified here, in fact I could probably revert the changes to JPA as they're redundant.  In addition, this should not cause problems switching back and forth between a frankfurt load and a guilin load, as it only creates the secondary indices if they do not exist.  (They should have been there all along anyway, so leaving them there if you switch back to frankfurt should be fine.)",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "4e883e6f3d0d28ca847f0ede6d125696285c5966",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-05-27 13:12:30.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> Patch Set 2:\n> \n> > Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1\n> > \n> > I have a question the counterpart changes on drools-applications that were already submitted, if I remember correctly was using JPA in java:   \n> > \n> > Do you think those changes would be compatible with a database that was created in Frankfurt, but for a drools-applications image from guilin?    The concern is trying to avoid the issue that API experiences with no being able to use database from previous release.\n> \n> I don't anticipate a problem.  The indices specified via JPA match those specified here, in fact I could probably revert the changes to JPA as they're redundant.  In addition, this should not cause problems switching back and forth between a frankfurt load and a guilin load, as it only creates the secondary indices if they do not exist.  (They should have been there all along anyway, so leaving them there if you switch back to frankfurt should be fine.)\n\nsounds good, thank you",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
